\section{Consider Mr. Hale’s evolution as a religious authority, legal authority, and community member. How does he change or stay the same and why? How can we interpret his presence in Act 3?}
\label{sec:orgb486a45}
\begin{itemize}
\item Legal authority
\begin{itemize}
\item Becomes disillusioned with the judicial system at end of Act 3.
\end{itemize}
\item Interpretation of presence
\begin{itemize}
\item Defends Proctor's right to defence in the judicial process
\item Voice of reason
\end{itemize}
\item Hale may defend Proctor and attempts to give him an opportunity to defend himself, but he also does not completely side with Proctor; In Act 2 he acts simultaneously as a respected member of the Salem community and as an agent of the court. He sometimes even comdemns Proctor in Act 3. He does crack on page 111.
\end{itemize}
